{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535057"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:53:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:53:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15285"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15285","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15285"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.04,0.23,0.33,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7976"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60929"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7976"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15285"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46374"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1167"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"1244"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3927"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"6112"},{"type":"tags","id":"6356"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19407"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29730"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32823"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60929"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following a rugby match where he sustained a heavy tackle and landed on his right shoulder. He developed immediate weakness and numbness in his right upper limb. Although improved, the symptoms have persisted for 24 hours. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is mild weakness (4/5) in right shoulder abduction and elbow flexion. Light touch sensation is reduced over the lateral aspect of the upper arm. Reflexes are symmetrically present. Range of motion of the cervical spine is full and pain-free. A right shoulder X-ray shows no bony abnormality.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound of the brachial plexus","Computed Tomography of the shoulder","Magnetic Resonance Imaging of the cervical spine","Magnetic Resonance Imaging of the shoulder","Electromyography and nerve conduction studies"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of a brachial plexus injury, commonly known as a \u0027stinger\u0027 or \u0027burner\u0027 in sports medicine. The mechanism of injury and pattern of symptoms are typical, involving a combination of weakness and sensory changes in the distribution of the upper trunk of the brachial plexus (C5-C6).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic Resonance Imaging of the cervical spine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation when symptoms persist beyond 24 hours. It can identify and exclude vertebral fractures, cervical nerve root impingement, disc herniation, or spinal cord signal changes that might be contributing to the ongoing symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of the brachial plexus\u003C/strong\u003E has limited utility in acute trauma and is more useful for identifying masses or tumours affecting the brachial plexus. It cannot reliably visualise preganglionic lesions or the proximal nerve roots.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed Tomography of the shoulder\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if there was concern about bony injury, but the X-ray has already excluded this and the clinical presentation is more consistent with a neurological injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic Resonance Imaging of the shoulder\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if there were concerns about rotator cuff or labral injury, which is not suggested by the clinical presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectromyography and nerve conduction studies\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful to determine the extent and location of nerve injury, but these are typically delayed until 3-4 weeks post-injury to allow time for denervation changes to develop.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Transient brachial plexus injuries (stingers/burners) commonly occur in contact sports due to traction or compression of the nerve roots.","MRI of the cervical spine is indicated when symptoms persist beyond 24 hours to exclude cervical spine pathology.","EMG/NCS studies are typically delayed until 3-4 weeks after injury to allow time for denervation changes to develop."],"references":["Belviso I, Palermi S, Sacco AM, Romano V, Corrado B, Zappia M, Sirico F. Brachial plexus injuries in sport medicine: clinical evaluation, diagnostic approaches, treatment options, and rehabilitative interventions. Journal of Functional Morphology and Kinesiology. 2020 Mar 30;5(2):22. Available online at ; https://www.mdpi.com/2411-5142/5/2/22","Hsu PC, Chang KV, Mezian K, Na\u0148ka O, Wu WT, Yang YC, Meng S, Ricci V, \u00d6z\u00e7akar L. Sonographic pearls for imaging the brachial plexus and its pathologies. Diagnostics. 2020 May 20;10(5):324. Available online at ; https://www.mdpi.com/2075-4418/10/5/324"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46374"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15285"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46374"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-14T16:01:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-14T16:03:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7976"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60929"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/45"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83e\uddbd","name":"Rehabilitation Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"